# Dart Conventions

## Style

- Follow `dart format`. Run `dart analyze` — fix all issues before committing.
- Use `internal` visibility via library-private (`_`) prefixes. Keep public API surface minimal.
- Prefer `final` and `const` everywhere they fit. Immutability by default.
- Reference existing patterns in the same package before inventing new ones.

## Naming

- Files: `snake_case.dart`. Classes: `PascalCase`. Variables/methods: `camelCase`.
- Services: `<Noun>Service`. Notifiers: `<Noun>Notifier`.
- Acronyms follow Dart style: `Url`, `Http`, `Id` (not all-caps).

## Error Handling

- Never swallow exceptions silently. Surface errors to the caller or log them.
- Use typed exceptions where the caller needs to distinguish error types.
- `try/catch` at the boundary (service/provider), not deep in domain logic.

## Async

- Use `async`/`await` over raw `Future` chaining.
- Use `switch` on sealed classes / union types for exhaustive state handling:
  ```dart
  return switch (state) {
    Loading() => ...,
    Error(:final exception) => ...,
    Data(:final value) => ...,
  };
  ```
- Cancel subscriptions and streams on dispose — no leaks.

## Testing

- Test public API and observable behavior, not implementation details.
- Mock external dependencies (storage, network) — no real I/O in unit tests.
- Use `dart test` with descriptive test names.

## Dependencies

- Run `dart pub get` after any `pubspec.yaml` change.
- Prefer packages already in use over adding new ones.
- Pin dependency versions. Run `dart pub upgrade` deliberately, not casually.
